The

It

but
at
this
date
(January

12th)
we
have
every
reason
to
hope
that
the
functional
result

will
be
as
satisfactory
as
the
improvement
in
patient's
appea-

rance.
He
can
already
feed
himself
with
ease,
though
no
dental

prosthesis
has
as
yet
been
attempted.
There
is
no
flowing
of

saliva,
and
speech
has
become
almost
normal.
No
dressing
is

necessary
in
spite
of
the
fact
that
the
last
operation
of
the

series
is
of
such
recent
date.
The
scars
will
eventually
dis-

appear
to
a
very
great
extent.
Moreover,
the
patient
can,
if

he
likes,
allow
the
hair
of
the
scalp
graft
to
grow,
in
which
case,

as
it
is
naturally
curly,
it
will
quite
passably
resemble
a
beard,

especially
if
skilfully
cut.
So
far
he
has
been
clean-shaven.

Unfortunately
the
hair
grows
at
one
spot
where
there
should

be
none
(viz.
on
the
inner
surface
of
the
floor
of
the
mouth),
and

has
to
be
cut
periodically.
In
our
experience,
however,
such

ectopic
hair
has
a
tendency
to
disappear,
constant
contact
with

the
saliva
being
apparently
unfavourable
to
its
growth.
